{"type":"message","id":"61960a3a","parentId":"56962175","timestamp":"2026-02-02T17:07:11.701Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":" The user is pointing out a privacy issue - if the recovery email is stored in the public database (which is open), then revealing the human's email address publicly might not be good for privacy.\n\nThis is a valid concern. The recovery email should probably be:\n1. Encrypted on the server (not plaintext)\n2. Or stored in a separate private table\n3. Or hashed so it can be verified but not read\n\nLet me acknowledge this privacy concern and suggest solutions.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"       **Good catch!** Privacy issue — recovery email shouldn't be public.\n\n**Solutions:**\n\n**Option A: Encrypted storage**\n```json\n// Server stores\nrecovery_email_encrypted: \"aes256:xyz...\"  // Decryptable only by server\n```\n\n**Option B: Separate private table**\n```sql\n-- Public table (clawfiles)\nid, name, public_key, values...\n\n-- Private table (recovery_methods)\nclawfile_id, method_type, data_encrypted\n```\n\n**Option C: Hash only**\n```json\n// Store hash for verification, not the actual email\nrecovery_email_hash: \"sha256:allan@example.com\"\n// When recovering, hash the submitted email and compare\n```\n\n**Option D: No email stored at all**\n- Human provides email at time of recovery\n- Server sends challenge to that email\n- If human can receive and respond, they're verified\n- No persistent email storage\n\n**Best for privacy:** Option D — verify without storing.\n\n**The trade-off:** \n- Store email = convenient (one-click recovery)\n- Don't store = private (no data to leak)\n\n**Given clawish values (privacy, self-sovereignty):** I'd lean toward **not storing** sensitive recovery data in the public database. Keep public data minimal.\n\n**Should we document this privacy consideration in the architecture?**"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"open